page.text: As part of Allston Event Management efforts, VHB conducted a data collection and observation plan during the 2014
Harvard-Yale football game. Vehicle, pedestrian, and bicycle counts were supplemented by in-field observations of
pedestrian flow, traffic congestion, safety, and parking operations and occupancy. The results of the observation
effort are summarized in this memorandum.
The Harvard-Yale game occurs every two years at Harvard Stadium. This year the 131
played on Saturday November 22, 2014 and began at 12:30 PM. This is the peak event in Harvard’s Allston campus;
approximately 31,000 people attended “The Game” in 2014. This year, interest and attendance remained high
throughout the duration of the game as Harvard came back to win 31-24 and claim sole possession of the Ivy League
Tailgating within the Allston Athletics Area began two hours prior to the start of the game and was allowed to
continue for one hour after the end of the game. Tailgating was restricted to designated areas and parking was not
allowed in the Allston Athletics Area. This year, ESPN’s College GameDay broadcasted live from the quad outside
Dillon Field House from 9:00 AM to 12:00 PM, adding an additional attraction to the day.
The Anderson Memorial Bridge, which connects Harvard’s Cambridge and Allston campuses, was under construction
by MassDOT (construction activities were suspended for the day). Due to the construction, only the easterly
(downstream) sidewalk was open and vehicular travel was limited to only one lane in each direction over the bridge.
At the Soldiers Field Road and North Harvard Street intersection, the Soldiers Field Road off-ramps and westbound
on-ramp were closed by the State Police to limit conflicts between vehicles and pedestrians. The closing of these
ramps also reduced operational issues typically caused by the temporary roadway modifications due to the
During discussions with Harvard staff about the ingress and egress patterns on game day, the ingress period before
the game was identified as the more critical period because the arrival patterns typically have stronger peaking
characteristics than the departures that can begin at halftime depending upon the nature of the game. Additionally,
entering vehicles are slowed by parking payment or permit processing during the ingress period. To understand the
more critical period, VHB conducted observations around the Allston Athletics Area from 9:30 AM to 12:30 PM. The
following summarizes the key findings of the observations by VHB staff:
In general, overall impacts to the adjacent area were observed to be minimal and the Harvard event
The majority of pedestrians were observed to enter the Athletics area via gates along North Harvard Street,
with the heaviest pedestrian flows coming from Cambridge via the Anderson Bridge and the Weeks
Footbridge. Pedestrians using the Weeks Footbridge crossed Soldiers Field Road and walked along the path
on its southern edge to North Harvard Street.
Harvard’s Spangler Lot and Soldiers Field Park Garage were heavily utilized for parking during The Game.
Activity at the Soldiers Field Park Garage peaked between 10:30 AM and 11:00 AM during which entering
vehicles queued onto Western Avenue causing minor impacts to traffic. Harvard operational staff directed
entering vehicles to form two lanes in Kresge Way, the driveway to Soldiers Field Park Garage, to reduce the
impacts on Western Avenue. Operations staff also collected parking fees from waiting vehicles within the
queue to improve the processing rate for vehicles to enter the garage.
Attendees were also observed to park in the Department of Conservation and Recreation (DCR) parking lots
adjacent to the Allston Athletics Area and cross Soldiers Field Road in the vicinity of Gate 14. The State Police
details at this location facilitated the crossings periodically to minimize impacts to Soldiers Field Road traffic
and provide a safe crossing location for pedestrians.
Limited spectator parking was observed in the neighborhood or in the Brighton Mills Parking Lot.
Minimal operational impacts were observed at the Barry’s Corner intersection. The Boston Police detail
located at the intersection helped to maintain smooth traffic operations and assist in the safe crossing of
The State Police closed the Soldiers Field Road off-ramps and westbound on-ramp which decreased the
potential for vehicle-pedestrian conflicts and improved overall safety at the intersection. From approximately
10:00 AM to 11:30 AM, a rolling queue extended along North Harvard Street from Soldiers Field Road to a
point between Harvard Way and Gordon Road, caused by the heavy pedestrian activity at the North Harvard
Street and Soldiers Field Road intersection.
Bus and passenger vehicle drop-offs along North Harvard Street near Gate 8 caused intermittent queues to
form along North Harvard Street while the vehicles unloaded. The northbound queues were observed to
extend at times from Gate 8 to between McCurdy Track and Barry’s Corner. Boston Police details and Harvard
operational staff assisted with buses dropping-off passengers on the eastern side of North Harvard Street by
directing passengers to a common crossing point and facilitating a safe crossing.

VHB staff observed transportation conditions associated with the Harvard-Yale football game on Saturday,
November 22, 2014 for a three-hour period from 9:30 AM to 12:30 PM. The observations were focused around the
Allston Athletics area, including Western Avenue, North Harvard Street, and Soldiers Field Road, and related to
parking, pedestrian movements, and traffic operations/safety. In general, overall impacts to the adjacent area were
observed to be minimal and the Harvard event management plan was executed well.
Attendees were directed to park in three Allston facilities: the Athletics area, Spangler Lot, and Soldiers Field Park
Garage. No issues were noted with overall parking supply or operations at any of the lots, with the exception of the
Soldiers Field Park Garage which is discussed in the Traffic Operations/Safety section. Event personnel and authorized
Harvard affiliates were directed to park in other Harvard-owned lots in Allston; Harvard personnel indicated that there
were no operational or supply issues at these lots.
Allston Athletics Area: Attendees could purchase parking passes prior to game day which allowed vehicular
access to the tailgate inside the Allston Athletics Area. The parking passes were associated with a specific
gate to reduce the need for vehicles to circulate around the Allston Athletics Area and limit the processing
time for entering vehicles. Parking passes for all gates were accepted at Gate 8.
Spangler Lot: Attendees who did not purchase parking passes ahead of time could pay to park in the
Spangler Lot. At 9:30 AM, when observations began, the lot was approximately 70 percent occupied and by
approximately 10:00 AM the lot was completely full.
Soldiers Field Park Garage: Similar to Spangler Lot, attendees who did not purchase parking passes ahead of
time could pay to park in the Soldiers Field Park Garage. The garage began to fill after the Spangler Lot
reached capacity, and between 10:30 and 11:00 AM there was a continuous two-lane queue on Kresge Way,
the entrance driveway into the garage.
Newell Boat House Parking Lot: A few attendees were observed to park in this lot. Only one group was
observed to cross Soldiers Field Road to access the Allston Athletics Area via Gate 20.
DCR Parking Lots: Although these lots are not owned nor operated by Harvard University, attendees were
observed to park and tailgate in the DCR parking lots adjacent to the Allston Athletics Area. These lots were
Neighborhood Parking: A window survey was completed at 8:00 AM and 1:00 PM in the adjacent
neighborhood. At 8:00 AM, parking occupancy in the neighborhood was observed to be at approximately 80
percent and occupancy decreased slightly to 75 percent at 1:00 PM. The greatest reduction in parking
occupancy between the morning and afternoon was observed on streets signed as “Resident Parking Only”
while streets with no parking restrictions (on Saturdays) remained at approximately the same occupancy
levels. A significant increase in parking occupancy between the morning and afternoon was only observed on
one street, Kingsley Street, which was observed to be approximately 60 percent occupied at 8:00 AM and 100
percent occupied at 1:00 PM. The results of the survey indicate that there was limited parking available in the
Brighton Mills Parking Lot: A window survey was completed at 8:00 AM and 1:00 PM in the Brighton Mills
Parking Lot. At 8:00 AM the parking lot was observed to be approximately 20 percent occupied and by 1:00
PM the parking occupancy increased to approximately 60 percent, however the increase in parking occupancy
could be attributed to patrons of the businesses located in the shopping center and not due to game
attendees. Multiple signs were located at the entrances and within the Brighton Mills parking lot indicating
“No Event Parking”. Based on the results of the survey, limited spectator parking was observed in the
Heavy pedestrian activity was observed in and around the Allston Athletics Area during the tailgating period prior to
the start of the football game at 12:30 PM. The majority of the pedestrians were observed to enter the Allston
Athletics Area via gates along North Harvard Street, with the heaviest pedestrian flows coming from Cambridge via
the Anderson Bridge and the Weeks Footbridge. Additional pedestrian demand was observed from the Spangler
(Business School) Lot and the Soldiers Field Park Garage and from MBTA bus stops along Western Avenue and North
At the intersection of North Harvard Street and Soldiers Field Road, State Police details closed the Soldiers Field Road
off-ramps and westbound on-ramp at approximately 10:00 AM to minimize vehicle and pedestrian conflicts. State
Police (located at Gates 14, 16, 20, and North Harvard Street at Soldiers Field Road) and Boston Police (located at Gate
8 and North Harvard Street at Western Avenue) helped to maintain vehicle operations and facilitate safe crossings for
pedestrians. Pedestrians generally utilized available sidewalks and controlled crossing locations.
Attendees were also observed to park in the DCR parking lots adjacent to the Allston Athletics Area and cross Soldiers
Field Road in the vicinity of Gate 14. The State Police details at this location would facilitate the crossings periodically
to minimize impacts to Soldiers Field Road traffic and provide a safe crossing location for the pedestrians.
Overall, VHB did not observe any major operational issues around the Allston Athletics Area. Event management
strategies at the following locations were observed to work well during the event:
Gates 14, 16, and 20: Minimal queueing was observed along Soldiers Field Road at the entrances to these
gates. State police were stationed at each gate to assist with traffic operations when necessary; specifically
helping pedestrians cross from the DCR parking lots at Gate 14, and coning off the left lane of Soldiers Field
Road eastbound in the vicinity of Gate 16 to allow for passenger car drop-offs. A VMS board was located
outside Gate 14 directing game day traffic. These measures limited the impacts to non-event traffic flow along
North Harvard Street at Soldiers Field Road: The State Police closed the Soldiers Field Road off-ramps and
westbound on-ramp which decreased the potential for vehicle-pedestrian conflicts and improved overall
Barry’s Corner: Minimal operational impacts were observed at the Barry’s Corner intersection. The Boston
Police detail located at the intersection helped to maintain smooth traffic operations and assist in the safe
The following minor operational issues caused by event traffic were noted:
Gate 8: Buses and passenger vehicles were observed to drop-off attendees along North Harvard Street
northbound and southbound near Gate 8, causing queues to form along North Harvard Street while the
vehicles unloaded. Boston Police details and Harvard operational staff assisted with buses dropping off
passengers on the eastern side of North Harvard Street by directing passengers to a common crossing point.
Each bus dwelled on North Harvard Street for an estimated ten minutes while passengers alighted.
North Harvard Street Northbound: From approximately 10:00 to 11:30 AM, a rolling queue extended from
Soldiers Field Road to between Harvard Way and Gordon Road, caused by the heavy pedestrian activity at the
North Harvard Street and Soldiers Field Road intersection. A second rolling queue (Figure 2) extended from
Gate 8 to a point between McCurdy Track and Barry’s Corner, caused by drop-off and pedestrian crossing
activity at Gate 8. Several vehicles were observed making mid-block u-turns along North Harvard Street to

page.text: Automatic traffic recorder (ATR) counts were conducted at two locations during the Harvard-Yale game: Western
Avenue and North Harvard Street. Figure 4 compares these counts to those conducted on a typical (i.e. non-event), or
control, day (Saturday November 15, 2014). As shown, Western Avenue and North Harvard Street traffic volumes on
Harvard-Yale game day were higher than those observed on a typical day, with the largest increase in volume during
the late morning and early afternoon hours which coincide with game arrival and departure activity. Overall, the daily
traffic volume on both Western Avenue and North Harvard Street showed an increase of approximately 20 percent
In addition, turning movement counts of both vehicular and pedestrian/bicycle traffic (TMCs) were conducted at
parking access locations and major gateways from 10:00 AM to 1:00 PM, including:
Western Avenue at Kresge Way/Genzyme driveway
Western Avenue at Batten Way/Hague Street
Western Avenue at North Harvard Street
North Harvard Street at Soldiers Field Road
The TMC data confirmed the findings of the in-field observations; there is a significant increase in pedestrian traffic to
the Allston Athletics Area on game day. Over the three hour count period, approximately 14,500 pedestrians traveled
through the intersection of North Harvard Street at Soldiers Field Road. This concentration of pedestrians is consistent
with the Cambridge location of student housing and transit services at Harvard Square. At the North Harvard Street
and Soldiers Field Road intersection, the Soldiers Field Road off-ramps and westbound on-ramp were closed which
reduced the overall traffic volume at the intersection. While approximately 1,500 pedestrians traveled through Barry’s
Corner, only 75 pedestrians were observed crossing Western Avenue from the south at the intersection.
Based on the discussion above, VHB offers the following potential improvements for potential inclusion in future plans
Consider routing buses to Gordon Road and utilizing it as a staffed unload position for attendee drop-off to
minimize traffic impacts along North Harvard Street. In the future, Academic Way could potentially be used as
a drop-off/pick-up area on game day.
Consider variable message signage at Barry’s Corner to notify motorists about “The Game,” the likelihood of
potential delays along North Harvard Street, and limited access to Soldiers Field Road.
Consider approaches and/or incentives which would encourage increased purchases of parking passes prior
to game day, such as offering discounts.
Consider parking management approaches which would encourage more simultaneous loading of Spangler
Lot and Soldiers Field Park Garage to reduce peak loading periods, such as directing more vehicles with pre-
purchased parking passes to use the Soldiers Field Park Garage.
